## {.smaller}

### Interview protocol (H2TX)

**A** — The community: strengths, weaknesses, and change
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;("place talk"; Schegloff 1972) *(open-ended)*

**B** — Multilingualism: personal background and attitudes
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;*(survey questions and Likert scale responses)*

**C** — Open-ended conversation questions *(includes Q15)*

**D** — Reading passage

## {.smaller}

### The "cringe question"

Inspired by Sneller & Barnhardt (2023) on pop-cultural elicitation:

::: {.fragment}
> **Interview question 15:**
> "Did you ever tell a story about another person, thinking the other person was not near you, but then turned around and saw that person was standing right next to you? Could you tell me about that? What happened?"
:::

::: {.fragment}
**The hypothesis:** A relatable, mildly embarrassing social situation (a *cringe* scenario) would generate:
:::

::: {.fragment}
- Natural, emotionally engaged narrative
- Phatic communion (Malinowski 1923) between fieldworker and speaker
- Casual, unmonitored speech — the vernacular
:::


